Cynthia's love, he tells his friend that he has no envy of his beautiful ¹ villa on the Tiber, with its costly furnitnre and lovely view, for he possessas in his love a joy and a wealth that far transcend all the joys and wealth of kings. From the Sixth Elegy of the First Book it appears that Tullus was the nephew of a man of distinction, L. Vocatius Tullus, who was consul in the year iac. 33, along with ν Octavian himself. This uncle, probably in the year 27 13.c., was setting out as proconsul to the senatorial province of Asia, and taking with him his nephew Tullus as his legatus.
